## Formatting Rules

Mechanical, deterministic conventions — no judgment call, so all Hard.

### Layout

- Line length: 100 characters max, 80 preferred.
- Two blank lines between top-level function and class definitions (distinct from the single blank line used to separate logical sections *inside* a function).
- Indentation: continuation lines get 2 indent levels — *except* array/dict/enum literals, which get only 1.
  - Continuation: `effect.interpolate_property(sprite, "transform/scale",` then indent 2 levels on the next line.
  - Array/dict/enum: `var party = [` then indent 1 level per entry.
- Trailing comma on the last entry of a multi-line array/dict/enum; no trailing comma on single-line ones.
- One space around operators and after commas (`position.x = 5`, not `position.x=5`); no spaces inside function calls or array indexing; single-line dict literals get a space just inside the braces (`{ key = "value" }`). Never use extra spaces to vertically align assignments.

### Comments

- Space after `#` and `##` for real comments; no space before commented-out code (`#print(...)`); `#region`/`#endregion` never get a space.
- Prefer comments on their own line; inline comments only for a few words.

### Quotes & Literals

- Double quotes by default; use single quotes only if that avoids more escapes than double quotes would. Double quotes win ties.
- Floats always carry a leading and trailing digit (`0.234`, `13.0` — never `.234` or `13.`).
- Hex literals use lowercase letters (`0xfb8c0b`).
- Use underscore separators in large numeric literals (`1_234_567_890`); skip separators under ~1,000,000.